leads.lead_text: Mature canopy composed mostly of opposite or subopposite, sessile or shortly petiolate pre-adult leaves
Mature canopy dominated by petiolate, disjunct adult leaves
Buds in 7s or more (sometimes fewer by abortion, but then scars usually apparent)
Buds in 3s
Juvenile leaves crenulate
Juvenile leaves not crenulate
Bark smooth, except sometimes near base of trunk
Bark rough or fibrous, extending at least to lower branches
Mallees; inflorescences 11–15-flowered; leaves strongly peppermint-scented when crushed
Small, spreading trees; inflorescences 7-flowered; leaves not peppermint-scented
Robust trees to 18 m tall; inner canopy dominated by ovate pre-adult leaves; outer canopy dominated by lanceolate adult leaves
Spindly trees to 8 m tall; canopy entirely of pre-adult leaves
Adult leaves with prominent pinnate side veins at wide angle to midrib
Adult leaves with acute, parallel or with irregularly pinnate side veins
Fruit more than 1 cm diam., operculum scar prominent (2–4 mm wide); disc raised or level; buds usually pedicellate
Fruit less than 1 cm diam., lacking prominent operculum scar; disc descending; buds sessile or shortly pedicellate
Bark rough; fruit cylindric or barrel-shaped, valves about level with rim
Bark smooth; fruit cylindric or obconical, valves exserted
Opercula long and finger-like, not or hardly tapering, slightly to much longer than hypanthium; peduncles strongly flattened; cultivated plants from Western Australia
Opercula shorter than hypanthium, or if ever longer than hypanthium then conical or beaked and peduncles terete or angular
Peduncles strap-like; flowers sessile, yellowish green; disc ascending; juvenile leaves scabrid
Peduncles not strap-like; flowers pedicellate, white to pale yellow; disc level to descending; juvenile leaves not scabrid
Hypanthia not fused; operculum warty
Hypanthia fused, infructescence ball-like; operculum not warty
Bark rough over main trunk; valves exserted
Bark smooth with small small curled flakes of persistent bark; valves level or slightly exserted
Juvenile leaves with stellate hairs; bark stringybark-type (except in some mallees of elevated sites in Grampians and East Gippsland)
Juvenile leaves without stellate hairs; bark various
Juvenile leaves hispid only for a few pairs; adult leaves strongly discolorous
Juvenile leaves hispid for numerous pairs; adult leaves concolorous or weakly discolorous
Buds warty
Buds not warty
Buds pedicellate, moderately warty
Buds sessile, markedly warty
Box bark extending to upper stem
Bark smooth throughout or a short, rough stocking present
Buds 1 or 3 (rarely 7); fruit 1.2–2 cm long, 1.6–3.2 cm diam.; valves strongly exserted
Buds 3 or 7; fruits 0.6–1.7 cm long, 1–2 cm diam.; valves exserted or at rim level
Smooth-barked mallees
Stringy-barked trees
Pedicels equal to or longer than buds; operculum beaked; opercular scar of fruit at widest part
Pedicels shorter than buds; operculum conical or obtuse; opercular scar of fruit above widest part
Buds clavate or slightly ovoid; fruits with disc ascending or folded
Buds fusiform; disc level or descending
Fruits 5–8 mm diam.; adult leaves elliptic to ovate, to 8 cm long
Fruits 8–12 mm diam.; adult leaves lanceolate, to 13 cm long
Fruits compacted into a tight ball; individual fruits compressed (nearly twice as wide as long) and tightly sessile
Fruits discrete, slightly wider than long, sessile or shortly pedicellate
Adult leaves green; fruits 6–10 mm diam.
Adult leaves blue-green; fruits 9–13 mm diam.
Buds warty
Buds non-warty
Fruits distinctly pedicellate, barrel-shaped or globose-truncate with valves recessed; staminal ring entire, tardily deciduous; buds lacking operculum scar
Fruits, stamens and buds not of the above combination, or stamens not as above and buds with an operculum scar
Bark rough throughout, hard, deeply furrowed, black (ironbark)
Bark largely smooth or fibrous and pale brown or rust-coloured
Inflorescences 3-flowered
Inflorescences 7-flowered

Inflorescences 7-flowered; fruit mostly <7 mm long
Buds sessile, fusiform, 7 or more, forming a stellate cluster
Buds not both sessile and fusiform, fewer than 7 in some species, not forming a stellate cluster
Juvenile leaves ovate-lanceolate; adult leaves with a dominant mid-vein
Juvenile leaves cordate; adult leaves with prominent, more or less parallel longitudinal venation
Tree; compact, blackish basal bark present; typically of cold-air drainage basins in subalps
Shrub; bark smooth; known only from exposed ridgetops of the Nunniong Plateau
Adult leaves with prominent, more or less parallel longitudinal venation
Adult leaves with a dominant mid-vein, lacking prominent longitudinal veins
Inflorescences simple umbels that are usually paired in axils
Inflorescences solitary simple umbels or panicles that are rarely paired in axils
Compact bark forming a stocking on lower trunk; disc of fruit flat, usually just below rim; Otways to eastern ranges
Rough, box-like bark extending to upper trunk; disc of fruit slightly domed; east Gippsland only
Buds and fruits square in cross-section; western mallees
Buds and fruits round in cross-section; trees or mallees
Inflorescences simple, axillary; fruits cylindrical or barrel-shaped
Inflorescences usually compound, occurring along a leafless, unbranched panicle: fruits cupular to subcampanulate
Inflorescences predominantly 3-flowered
Inflorescences predominantly 7- or more-flowered
Buds waxy; trees or mallees of eastern ranges
Buds non-waxy
Juvenile leaf pairs connate, often dried and trapped in canopy
Juvenile leaves non-connate
Disc of fruit descending
Disc of fruit ascending or approximately level with rim
Operculum strongly beaked, wider than the hypanthium
Operculum conical, as wide as the hypanthium
Bark smooth; branchlets and buds copiously waxy
Bark rough at least to mid-trunk; branchlets and buds lightly waxy
Rough bark forming a stocking to mid-trunk; fruits ovoid
Rough bark extending to major branches; fruits obconical or subcampanulate
Juvenile leaves lanceolate (rarely ovate)
Juvenile leaves orbicular or cordate
Buds and fruit more than 1 cm long, distinctly pedicellate and pendulous; disc descending
Buds and fruit not more than 1 cm long, sessile or shortly pedicellate, usually erect; disc ascending
Mallees or small, often slender trees to 12 m tall; bark greenish; rare in far-eastern subalps
Medium to tallish trees (commonly more than 10 m tall); bark white or pinkish; widespread, from lowlands to montane forests
Juvenile leaves glaucous, orbicular, often emarginate; adult leaves bluish, less than 15 cm long; fruits less than 6 mm diam.
Juvenile leaves blue-green, cordate; adult leaves green, more than 20 cm long; fruits 6–9 mm diam.
Inflorescences in terminal leafless panicles, either branched or unbranched
Inflorescences simple, axillary (rarely borne within the crown on leafless sections of branches)
Buds angled, waxy; fruits cylindrical
Buds round in cross-section, non-waxy; fruits not cylindrical
Canopy dominated by ovate to suborbicular or deltoid leaves
Canopy dominated by lanceolate leaves
Juvenile leaves broadly ovate; smooth, copper-coloured bark on upper trunk
Juvenile leaves orbicular, emarginate; bark box type, extending at least to major branches

Bark mostly smooth; south-west of Edenhope only
Bark box-like
Juvenile leaves linear-lanceolate; canopy leaves dull green to glaucous; bark rough to small branches
Juvenile leaves ovate-lanceolate or orbicular; canopy leaves green; bark rough on trunk or extending to base of larger branches

Juvenile leaves ovate-lanceolate; fruits 3- or 4-valved; west of a line between Melbourne and Albury
Immature fruits with needle-like style remnants extending prominently above the rim
Fruits without prominent needle-like style remnants
Juvenile leaves  ovate; operculum horn-shaped
Juvenile leaves heath-like, either linear or narrow-elliptical; operculum rounded or apiculate at the apex
Bark not stringybark-type, or if stringybark, not extending to branches (E. delegatensis)
Bark thick and fibrous ('stringybark-type'), extending at least to lower branches
Bark longitudinally furrowed, stringy; juvenile and adult leaves distinctly assymetric
Bark longitudinally furrowed, but not stringy, leaves not distinctly assymetric
Juvenile leaves orbicular; buds waxy
Juvenile leaves linear-lanceolate, lanceolate, ovate-lanceolate or elliptic; buds non-waxy
Juvenile leaves lustrous and green
Juvenile leaves dull pale green, blue-green to glaucous

Canopy dull or sublustrous, blue-green or grey-green; widespread on and south of the Great Dividing Range
Juvenile leaves ovate to elliptical, 1–3 cm wide
Juvenile leaves linear or linear-lanceolate, falcate, less than 1 cm wide
Adult leaves sublustrous, blue-green; fruit with short, thick pedicels
Adult leaves dull, blue-grey; fruit with slender pedicels (often as long as fruit)
Juvenile leaves dull, glaucous; fruits distinctly pedicellate, 3–4 mm diam.
Juvenile leaves pale green; fruits sessile or subsessile, 4–6 mm diam.
Bark smooth throughout or a short basal stocking of rough bark present
Persistent rough bark extending to at least upper trunk
Inflorescences borne on leafless part of branches (never in leaf axils); adult leaves discolorous;  fruit barrel- or urn-shaped, slightly ribbed, usually more than 1 cm long
Inflorescences axillary (sometimes appearing on stem where leaves have fallen off); leaves and fruits not as above
Buds horn-shaped or globoid and beaked
Buds not as above

Operculum not ribbed

Small tree with persistent grey to black rough bark on lower trunk
Mallee with smooth bark (sometimes with semi-attached ribbons persisting at base)
Adult leaves broadly lanceolate; operculum strongly ribbed
Adult leaves lanceolate; operculum faintly ribbed
Trees
Mallees
Small, spindly tree to 8m tall; rare in central part of Little Desert
Small, few-trunked spreading trees to tallish, forest trees

Juvenile leaves ovate, petiolate, disjunct
Fruits urn-shaped; branchlets non-waxy
Fruits barrel-shaped; branchlets lightly waxy

Juvenile leaves petiolate

New season’s growth green; buds non-waxy

Canopy dominated by ovate adult leaves; pedicels shorter than fruits; fruits 4–8 mm diam.

Fruit obconical

Juvenile leaves orbicular, emarginate; adult markedly glandular
Juvenile leaves lustrous, green
Juvenile leaves subglaucous or glaucous
Forest trees to 65 m tall; juvenile leaves lanceolate to ovate-lanceolate
Small trees to 25 m tall; juvenile leaves broadly ovate, suborbicular or orbicular
Seedling stems not winged; Mt Martha (Mornington Peninsula) area only
Seeding stems winged; west of Melbourne
Fruits 6–8 mm long, 5–6 mm diam.; pedicels slender, 2–3 mm wide
Fruits 8–13 mm long, 7–11 diam.; pedicels 3–4 mm wide
Operculum 4–6 mm long; fruits 9–13 mm long, 9–11 mm diam.
Operculum 3–4 mm long; fruits 7–10 mm long, 7–9 mm diam.
Bark rough and thickish on lower trunk, loosely attached above; trees often of poor form, on drier sites

Adult leaves with toothed margins

Disc at rim level or descending

Inflorescences 7–11-flowered; fruits not globose-truncate; leaves peppermint-scented or not

Adult leaves more than 7 cm long; disc not white
Buds and branchlets waxy
Buds and branchlets non-waxy
Fruits 10–13 mm diam.
Fruits  5–9 mm diam.
Adult leaves wider than 2 cm; fruits tightly sessile
Adult leaves to 1.5 cm wide; fruits pedicellate
Fruits 6–9 mm diam.; valves at rim level
Fruit 3–7 mm diam.; valves enclosed

Juvenile leaves dull, blue-green to glaucous; western Victoria

Trees or mallees; disc level, descending, or sometimes slightly raised at the perimeter but descending toward the valves (annular); valves enclosed or level

Juvenile leaves orbicular or cordate; margins crenulate

Adult leaves bluish; immature fruits waxy
Adult leaves green; immature fruits non-waxy

Juvenile leaves broadly ovate, non-emarginate
Seedling stems winged; fruits 9–13 mm long
Seedlings stems not winged; fruits 7–10 mm long

Buds clavate or ovoid; fruits not obconical

Juvenile leaves broadly ovate or suborbicular; adult leaves ovate or broadly ovate, more than 2.5 cm wide

Buds pedicellate; operculum not ribbed

Bark compact, hard or peppermint type, if thickish, tending to be longitudinally ridged

Intramarginal vein remote; fruits 5-valved
Intramarginal vein not remote; fruits 3–4-valved
Mallees; bark mostly smooth
Small often few-stemmed trees; bark rough over much of trunk

Juvenile leaves broadly lanceolate or ovate, petiolate, disjunct
Juvenile leaves lanceolate (narrow to broad) or ovate, sessile, opposite
Rough bark compact, ironbark-like, extending to upper trunk; fruits barrel-shaped or globose-truncate
Rough bark soft peppermint to somewhate stringybark-like, including harder fibres (prickly when crushed), extending to secondary branches; fruits obconical or somewhat pear-shaped

Buds non-waxy
Adult leaves green, 2–4 cm wide
Adult leaves subglaucous; 0.8–1.7 cm wide

Juvenile leaves lanceolate (narrow to broad), 0.8–3 cm wide; adult leaves narrowly lanceolate to lanceolate, less than 2 cm wide
Adult leaves dull or slightly lustrous, blue-green; fruits 4–6 mm diam.; Wilsons Promontory
Adult leaves lustrous, green; fruits 7–9 mm diam.; Gippsland Lakes area
Adult leaves green, to 1.6 cm wide; fruits 5–6 mm diam.; Little Desert
Adult leaves blue-green, to 3.5 cm wide; fruits 6–8 mm diam.; Otways, Grampians and south western Victoria
